Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm
wide chips (no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil, sprinkle over the
@Chinese Five Spice{1%sachet}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to
coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{150%grams}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pat the @basa fillets{2} dry with #kitchen paper{}. Lay the fish on a lined
large baking tray.

Spread the @sambal paste{30%grams} over the fillets. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

When the chips are halfway through baking, add the fish to the middle shelf of
the oven and bake until cooked through, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish. It's cooked
> when opaque in the middle.

While the basa bakes, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on
medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the green beans and stir-fry until starting to char,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic, then turn the heat down to medium and cook for
~{1%minute} more. Add a splash of water and immediately cover with a #lid{}
or some #foil{}.

Cook until the beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

When the basa has 3 mins remaining, drizzle the @sweet chilli sauce{32%grams}
over the fillets.

Return to the oven for the remaining cooking time, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When everything's ready, share the basa fillets between your plates and sprinkle
with the @roasted white sesame seeds{5%grams}.

Serve with the garlic green beans and Five Spice chips alongside. Add some
@mayonnaise{3%tbsp} for dipping.

Enjoy!